Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Brucellosis is the generic name used for the animal and human infections caused by several species of the genus_Brucella, mainly _Brucella abortus_, _B. melitensis_ and _B. suis_. In animals, brucellosis is usually associated with late-term abortions in females and inflammation in the male reproductive tract.

Infection with Brucella in cattle is mainly caused by _B. abortus_. The disease is known as "Bovine brucellosis", "Contagious abortion" and "Bang's disease" (after the Danish veterinarian, who discovered _B. abortus_ as the cause of contagious abortion in cattle in 1887).

The main reservoir of _B. melitensis_ are sheep and goats, with the main symptom being abortions. Spillover into cattle from this reservoir is rather common in countries suffering endemic _B. melitensis_ in sheep and goats. _B. melitensis_ is not abortifacient in cattle but will infect the udders, followed by a massive discharge of the highly pathogenic bacteria in the milk and consequent human infections.

The source of the infection reported from cattle in Haute-Savoie is likely to be sought in wild fauna in the mountains, focusing on chamois [_Rupicapra rupicapra_]; please refer to 20120414.1101283 (human infection) and to 20121013.1340461 (reference to Mod PMB's commentary).

Brucella infection is readily transmissible to humans, causing acute febrile illness - 'undulant fever' - which may progress to a more chronic form and can also produce serious complications affecting the musculoskeletal, cardiovascular, and central nervous systems. - Mods.AS & CRD

